SIMPLE: fustian
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fustian
<hw>Fus"tian</hw> <pr>(f⟦ucr⟧s"ch⟦ait⟧n; 106)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[OE. <ets>fustan</ets>, <ets>fustian</ets>, OF.
<ets>fustaine</ets>, F. <ets>futaine</ets>, It. <ets>fustagno</ets>, fr.
LL. <ets>fustaneum</ets>, <ets>fustanum</ets>; cf. Pr.
<ets>fustani</ets>, Sp. <ets>fustan</ets>. So called from
<ets>Fust⟦amac⟧t</ets>, i. e., Cairo, where it was made.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A kind of coarse twilled cotton or cotton and linen
stuff, including corduroy, velveteen, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An inflated style of writing; a kind of writing in
which high-sounding words are used, above the dignity of the thoughts or
subject; bombast.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Claudius . . . has run his description into the most wretched
<qex>fustian</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fustian</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fustian
<hw>Fus"tian</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Made of
fustian.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Pompous; ridiculously tumid; inflated; bombastic;
<as>as, <ex>fustian</ex> history</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Walpole.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fustianist</ent>⟦br⟧
